---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

// About Stacey — the longer page. Family origin story, philosophy,
// who this is for. Wider measure for narrative breathing.
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Stacey"
  description="About Stacey — the financial coach behind Yellow Legal Pad. Her father, her path, and how she works."
>
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="story-heading">
    <div class="column-wide">
      <h1 id="story-heading">A desk in the hallway and a yellow legal pad</h1>
      <p class="dek">Financial coaching for life's biggest transitions.</p>

      <!-- Image slot — pending warm abstract imagery from Stacey
           (legal pad and pen, desk scene, natural textures; no
           stock photos of women). See TODO_STACEY.md § Brand
           imagery. Uncomment alongside the Pass 459 follow-up.
      <figure class="page-image">
        <img src="/images/about-hero.jpg" alt="" />
      </figure>
      -->

      <p>
        Every Friday without fail, Stacey's father came home from
        work, sat down at the small desk in the hallway, and paid
        the bills. Checks written by hand, put in envelopes, done.
        Then errands &mdash; the bank, gas, the deli for his lunch
        meat, sometimes the wine shop. Same order every week.
      </p>

      <p>
        He was careful with money. Quietly, consistently, without
        drama. His Dutch mother had warned Stacey's mother before
        they married that she was marrying someone frugal to a
        fault. She wasn't wrong.
      </p>

      <p>
        But he retired at 57 on a modest salary. One trusted
        advisor, one yellow legal pad, the same silver Cross pen
        he'd been given for a Xerox work anniversary. Thirty
        years of doing the same sensible things, week after week,
        without making it complicated.
      </p>

      <p>
        Stacey grew up watching that. The Friday ritual. The desk.
        The errands. The lesson that if you wanted something
        special &mdash; a new bike, something above and beyond
        &mdash; you paid half yourself.
      </p>

      <p>
        Nobody talked about money as something to panic about. It
        was just something you showed up for, every Friday, and
        took care of.
      </p>

      <p>
        The practice she runs today is carrying that forward.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* "How she got here" section is held until Stacey provides the
